  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
        <div rend="parallel">
          <p xml:id="KT103-kilavi">paruvaṅ kaṇṭu aḻinta talaimakaḷ tōḻikkuc colliyatu.</p>
          <p xml:lang="en">Uttered to the confidante by HER who is desolate at the sight of the season.</p>
          </div>
          


        <div rend="parallel">
            <lg xml:id="KT103">
<l>                kaṭumpuṉa ṟoṭutta naṭuṅkaña raḷḷaṟ</l>
<l>                kavirita ḻaṉṉa tūvic cevvā</l>
<l>                yiraitēr nāraik kevva mākat</l>
<l>                tūun tuvalait tuyarkūr vāṭaiyum</l>
<l>                vārār pōlvarnaṅ kātalar</l>
<l>                vāḻēṉ pōlva ṟōḻi yāṉē.</l>
             </lg>
            <lg xml:lang="en">
           <l rend="indent">Even with the north wind,</l>
           <l rend="indent3">abounding in the misery of spattering spray,</l>
           <l rend="indent">so that the mire, trembling sorrow, stored by the quick flood,</l>
           <l rend="indent">becomes troublesome to the flamingo<note place="foot">The colour description makes one rather think of a flamingo, but that does not fit in well with the behaviour (looking for prey, and moving singly). The explanation adduced by TVG is that <term xml:lang="ta">nārai-s</term> (by him translated as "cranes" which need mean nothing in particular) turn a little red in colour when they are aged. He gives another reference in Nacc. on Kali 124 where <term xml:lang="ta">nārai-s</term> are compared to brahmin sanyasins who traditionally wear red clothes.</note> searching for prey,</l>
           <l rend="indent">with red mouth [and] feathers like the petals of the silkcotton,</l>
           <l>he doesn't seem to come, our lover.</l>
           <l>It seems I won't  live, friend.</l>
            </lg>
        </div>
    </body>
